FILL YOUR CUP FIRST. 
•
for so long, i constantly tried to pour from an empty cup. i thought the only thing that mattered was my performance on the track and in workouts. 
•
my life became consumed only by running, which meant if i had a bad race or workout, i felt like a failure because running was all i thought i was. when i started filling my cup with MORE than running… i found more of who AMBER was. 
•
amber wasn’t a “runner” running was just something she loves. she also loves sharks, surfing, peanut butter, rock climbing, hiking, drawing, and anything that makes her feel free. 
•
don’t forget about the things that bring you joy, no matter how small they may seem. life is so much more than your sport and YOU are so much more than your sport. realizing that can help you fill your cup and become an even better athlete AND human💜

2022 was by far the best year of my life. most of my life, my entire identity has been wrapped up in being a runner and becoming a pro runner. i put so much pressure on myself to become something that i realize i don’t want to be. i feel like, over this past year, i found the little amber in me that i lost when i became obsessed with running and developed my eating disorder. 
•
I’ve lived more life this year than ever before. some core memories from 2022 are going 22 miles across the grand canyon, road-tripping from tennessee to arizona, shark diving, rock climbing, surfing, skateboarding, tree jumping, sleeping on the beach, sleeping at a gas station, countless nights looking at stars, far too many all nighters, camping, getting four tattoos, cutting bangs and so much fkn more. 
•
i’ve rediscovered the things that once brought me joy but that i stopped doing because i filled my time with things that didn’t matter to me. this year i’ve realized how much i crave freedom, and without it, i tend to run. i’ll find it in any way i can. this can be a blessing and a curse, so i’m learning to work with it. 
•
i don’t know what’s gonna happen in 2023, but i know it’s going to bring countless adventures, laughs, tears, and life lessons. and i’m so fkn ready to ride the wave🏄🏼‍♀️👽☀️🛹

after a few rough weeks of going through a bit of an “identity crisis” and lots of mental blocks, i finally feel like i’m taking a step in the right direction. 
•
i have felt lost in the idea of who “amber” is because my whole life, i saw myself as just a runner. after realizing that's not who i am, I’ve been faced with the question in my head of what’s next? who’s amber? what’s my purpose? what do i wanna do with this life? 
•
i now know that i don’t need to know. It's OKAY not to know. instead of trying to figure out EXACTLY who amber wants to be, i’m just going to start following what makes my heart and soul feel full each day. I know if i do that and have gratitude for the people/ opportunities around me, everything will fall into place exactly as it should🫶🏼
•
having this mindset has opened me up to knew creative ideas that have MADE ME SO HAPPY!!! like starting the Be Positive Pod, starting my first PRODUCT LINE (working with SO MANY of you all to create such beautiful designs🫶🏼💜🥹), creating a youtube video and overall directing my focus to things that matter most to me🏄🏼‍♀️
•
here’s your reminder you don’t need to have it figured out, you don’t need to live your life based on what others think, and do what makes YOU the happiest version of yourself☀️
•

this week is national eating disorder awareness week. back in 2019, this was the week i decided to be open about having an eating disorder💚
•
being open was terrifying… it meant that i was finally facing the reality of what i was doing to my body. i was releasing a little bit of that control i was desperately grasping onto. it was the start of a very long and rocky road of recovery. 
•
when i think of the girl i once was… i immediately see her as weak, but then i remember SHE was the one who got me to where i am now. SHE was the one who kept putting one foot in front of the other. she may have been extremely lost but also incredibly strong and courageous. i thank her for never giving up💓 if only she could see us now and how worth it recovery has been🥹 my mind and body are still recovering, but each year i get stronger and my zest for life continues to GROW. 
•
YOU are so much more than your ED. there is SO much more to life than what your ED tells you. 💓 who i am now is COMPLETELY different than the girl i was, and for that, i am GRATEFUL. 
•
if you are struggling, i encourage you to reach out for help, i could NOT have gone through recovery on my own. i love you. you got this!

howdy. i know i haven’t been telling y’all much about how i’ve been doing. so much has happened over the past couple of months I’ve needed to take a step back. there are so many layers to everything, but i’ve been going to therapy once a week, working through a lot. i’ve been in a weird grief period of letting go of my old self and situations. right now, I’m in a much better spot than i have been this entire year.
•
as many of you know, i have dealt with shin issues for about a year in my left shin. after christmas break, my shin pain(MTSS- Medial Tibial Stress Syndrome) went away but was followed by a much sharper pain in my opposite shin. i was in a boot for about two weeks and then was able to start running a little after a couple weeks! but the pain has recently come back, so i will be getting an MRI this weekend.
•
although this injury has been super frustrating….i wouldn’t change it. i get emotional every time i think about where i was just a couple of months ago—trapped in a cycle of just needing to get through and perform what i could. i’ve hurt and overworked my mind and body so much this year…she has every right to be angry. 
so now she deserves love. 
she deserves healing. 
she deserves what i thought i couldn’t give her months ago. 
•
this injury has taught me my strength to stand up for myself. this injury has taught me who AMBER is. this injury has opened my eyes and helped me get clarity that i may have never reached. i’m NOT a runner. running is something that i do. running is something that i love with all of my heart. but running does NOT define me. 
running does NOT define my worth. 
running will be there when i get back…a smarter version of myself. my goals now are simple. happy and healthy. with that, everything else will come🫶🏼

last night i took the time to read through my ED recovery journal. 
•
this is the first time i have ever read in depth the things that i wrote back in 2018-2019. I was reading so much about how i wanted to be happy. i just kept writing, “i want to be happy” and “i will be happy”. 
•
i now know that the feeling of happiness is temporary. but the feeling of joy is something that lasts. during this time, i was chasing after things that would bring me this superficial level of “happiness”. my happiness came from controlling the way i ate, looked, and performed. if i lost any of this control, i lost happiness. 
•
reading this gave me so much peace in knowing how far i’ve come. these things do not bring lasting JOY. joy is found through finding meaning, purpose, and connection throughout life… not based on the food you eat, how your body looks, or your performance
•
 if you are struggling with feeling as though your happiness is based on these things, here’s your reminder to focus your energy on the bigger things that bring true meaning and joy to life. human connections, spiritual well-being, experiences, and purpose🌞🌺🫶🏼

why do we always have the feeling we aren’t good enough? constantly feeling like there’s something that needs to be fixed or changed.
•
i’ve spent so much time picking apart my body, feeling like i was a failure or that i should look different. one day confidence could be through the roof….followed by a day feelin like shit 💩 but my body hasn’t changed in those two days. my mind, what i’m telling myself, and what i’m consuming(on social media) probably has. 
•
I’ve spent many days wishing I had somebody else’s body. There have probably been people who wish they had my body.
and there’s probably someone out there wishing they looked like you or maybe even their younger self, an older version of themselves, more muscular, more “toned,” or just able to change any aspect of themselves that isn’t deemed “perfect.”
•
we waste so much time wishing we were different that we miss out on the life that is RIGHT. IN. FRONT. OF. US. here’s your reminder today no one gives a shit what you look like, and who you are as a person is what people are gonna remember about you. be gentle on yourself today💘🫶🏼

3 things I wish I had learned earlier in my fitness/lifting journey!🌻
•
1) comparing your journey to others won’t help you reach your goals faster. someone else’s path is NOT your path!
•
2) restricting your food intake is hindering your muscle growth and strength.  for your muscles to grow and recover they need FUEL! your body can not run optimally on limited food…just like a car cannot run without gas:) eat up😘
•
3) not taking rest days does not make you better. REST SO YOUR MUSCLES CAN BUILD AND RECOVER. i’ve always felt sooo much better when i include rest days into my week and have even noticed SO much more growth and strength from allowing my muscles to REST. it also helps my workouts become 10x better;)
•
📸 @hannah_kacer11

“you’re too pretty to struggle with your body, image,” and “you’re too fit not to like your body”…... i’ve heard these comments a countless number of times.
•
It makes me sad because it reminds me of how easy it is for people that are struggling to get ignored because they don’t “look” the part of whatever they may be struggling with. but the truth is there’s no “look”…. ANYONE can struggle, and EVERYONE deserves help🫶🏼
•
struggling with body dysmorphia/ bad body image can be frustrating. one second, you can feel great and confident, then the next, like, “wait, when did i turn into a marshmallow”. 
•
something that has helped me is to remember that thoughts are just thoughts, and the voice in your head is nothing more than a voice…. we are always SO much more critical of ourselves than anyone ever is of us. 
•
treat yourself like you would treat your best friend. the more we tear ourselves down and talk negatively to ourselves… the more we believe it. but the more positively we speak to ourselves. THE MORE WE BELIEVE IT. make complementing yourself a habit! you glow differently when you are confident in who you are inside and out❤️
•
take care of your body, and i promise even though it’s hard right now, the negative thoughts and emotions will pass. you WILL feel good again. reach out to someone and TALK. you don’t need to struggle alone:)

no matter how small you get. no matter how much you restrict yourself, it will never be enough for the ED voice in your head. you will NEVER satisfy the voice in your head. 
•
having an eating disorder feels like a never-ending battle, and the longer i’ve lived with it, the more I’ve realized no matter what i look like, it will never be enough. it will never be enough for my ED. so instead of listening to the voice and continuing an ongoing cycle, we must focus on health. how can i be the healthiest version of myself mentally, physically, and spiritually? this can only happen with balance, human connection, and self-acceptance. all of which an ED takes away from you. 
•
i’m writing this because i’ve learned that being open, vulnerable, and raw on here doesn’t only help me, but it’s helping so many others. being a student athlete is fkn hard in itself. balancing that with disordered thoughts about food/body image is even more challenging. 
•
What has helped me when i’m struggling is:
#1 SUPPORT SYSTEM: talking to my boyfriend, writing him letters about exactly what’s going on in my brain, calling my mom, and even talking with other teammates struggling. 
#2 WRITING: when i begin to have bad thoughts, i immediately start writing. whatever is in my brain, i write out, and it helps me see how bananas i sound🙈 
#3 FUEL BODY: this seems obvious, but it’s incredible the difference in thoughts you will have when you fuel your body compared to when you neglect it. the brain can not function properly without fuel.

it’s crazy to think that something called an “eating disorder” can actually have nothing to do with food itself. it’s a mental disorder rooted in something so much deeper.
•
I’ve recently really started to work on challenging myself in recovery. it’s so easy to get in a comfortable spot in recovery where you kinda stop making progress…. almost like a “recovery plateau.”
i feel like i was in that for a while, then took a few steps back, and now making many steps forward.
 •
i’ve been eating foods that my childhood self used to LOVE and foods i told myself were off limits. it’s made me realize how much EDs can truly be rooted in control. when i challenge foods, or i eat foods that are not considered “safe,” then it tells me i have lost control, i am a failure, going to gain weight, get slow, and lose progress. THIS 👏 IS 👏 NOT 👏 TRUE👏. one thing i once heard was that if the ED says it….it’s probably a lie. and that’s the truth. 
•
so here’s your reminder today that ALL FOODS FIT and challenge yourself no matter how uncomfortable it may be❤️💛 i’ve had a rough day today after being in a high stress state and then challenging myself with a food fear. my ed was searching for control through food, but i didn’t give it that. 
•
what’s hard in the moment is only temporary, and you WILL get through what you are facing….stronger than ever. that little ed voice in your head is lying🫶🏼

i’ve been thinking, and i want to talk about balancing both ED recovery and having athletic goals. when balancing these two goals, it’s important to remember that ED recovery comes before ANYTHING else. mental health is just like physical health and is just as important(if not more). at the beginning of my recovery, i took time off to let my body rest, but now it’s about knowing how to balance both! and with that comes holding yourself accountable and asking yourself tough questions about your specific goal each training session. 
•
reaching big goals in your sport short and long term requires a lot of hard work… but it also requires a lot of REST. i know resting can be hard when having an unhealthy relationship with food/exercise, so i want to remind you today that if resting is challenging because of the fear of not moving enough, losing fitness, or needing to “earn your food,” then you need to take a step back, take that rest you know you need and remind yourself of your TRUE goals. success and longevity in this sport, LONGTERM. 
•
today i had to remind myself of this very thing… i’ve had a huge load of training over the past week and never got in my full rest day… so i decided to take today easier and pull back the volume to let my mind/body rest. this made me feel guilty and lazy. i then realized that was my ED talking because AMBER knows that rest is exactly what my body needed today to help me become a better athlete. so, instead of forcing my body to go through another large training day… i decided to let my body recover❤️ and i’m reminding you to do the same🫶🏼
